the condictor expanded and contracted form the heat [rodiced form cerrernt flowing through it that the condetors became brittle and the electrical bond was lost through this process.  This could be a potentially dangerous situation ad should not be ignored!\r\n\r\nLastly there could be a problem further up stream of the device that currently does not work.', 'faq', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-4', '', '', '2011-02-11 23:44:10', '2011-02-11 23:44:10', '', '9', 'http://eazyelectric.dev/9-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('57', '1', '2011-01-27 00:58:19', '2011-01-27 00:58:19', 'This is our frequently asked questions page.', 'faq', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-27 00:58:19', '2011-01-27 00:58:19', '', '9', 'http://eazyelectric.dev/9-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('59', '1', '2011-02-11 23:53:04', '2011-02-11 23:53:04', '<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em><strong>Why do recepticle outlets just stop working?</strong></em></span> Receptcles are simple devices that over time, or through manufacturer defect sometimes simply just break, and need to be replaced.  Another possible answer is that from over time the wires that bring power to the recepticle have expanded and contracted form the heat produced from current flowing through it that the conductors became brittle and the electrical bond was lost through this process.  This could be a potentially dangerous situation ad should not be ignored!\r\n\r\nLastly there could be a problem further up stream of the device that currently does not work.', 'faq', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-5', '', '', '2011-02-11 23:53:04', '2011-02-11 23:53:04', '', '9', 'http://eazyelectric.dev/9-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('205', '1', '2012-02-28 19:54:11', '2012-02-28 19:54:11', '<img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-198\" title=\"Electrical for hot tub\" src=\"http://www.eazyelectric.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/iStock_000010019905Small-1.jpg\" alt=\"Electrical for hot tubs\" width=\"550\" height=\"365\" />\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to consider while planning your hot tub install:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Are you able and willing to help with the installation?</strong> Some customers have preferred to do the required digging for the conduit that runs from the house to where the Spa will rest.  This will reduce the work for electricians and will save you money.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Be sure to ask when purchasing your Spa if the electrical disconnect is included or if you have to purchase this separate. </strong> If the disconnect is included make sure to ask for it from the ones delivering the spa.  I say this as they run about $100 and the people delivering my tub tried to keep it!</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Be aware that it is a code requirement to have a receptacle outlet located not less than 6 feet from, and not more than 20 feet from, the inside wall of the spa.</strong> This is a quick fix if your home does not currently have one.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Installing a hot tub is a dangerous job.</strong> There is some residential work that any do-it-your self-er can handle, but I would encourage you to hire a qualified electrician for this project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nI\'ll admit I knew becoming a electrician in Seattle was going to involve  crawling around in boiling hot attics with itchy insulation ending up  everywhere on me, like sand after a day at the beach.  Then there\'s the  awesome smell of dead rats and other lovely little critters I find in  the crawl spaces under houses that can put a damper on my day as an  electrical contractor.  But I will say that I don\'t mind it as much when  I know that at the end of the day I am providing a service that will  bring my customer a truly relaxing experience!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Electrical for hot tubs: Things to consider', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '62-revision-19', '', '', '2012-02-28 19:54:11', '2012