3', '', '', '2011-02-12 21:12:27', '2011-02-12 21:12:27', '', '66', 'http://www.eazyelectric.com/66-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('161', '1', '2011-04-25 22:01:35', '2011-04-25 22:01:35', 'There are a few important things to consider while planning your hot tub install:\r\n\r\n1.)  Are you able and willing to help with the installation?  Some customers have preferred to do the required digging for the conduit that runs from the house to where the Spa will rest.  This will reduce the work for electricians and will save you money.\r\n\r\n2.)  Be sure to ask when purchasing your Spa if the electrical disconnect comes with it or if you have to purchase this separate.  If the disconnect is included make sure to ask for it from the ones delivering the spa.  I say this as they run about $100 and the people delivering my tub tried to keep it!\r\n\r\n3.)  Be aware that it is a code requirement to have a receptacle outlet located not less than 6 feet from, and not more than 20 feet from, the inside wall of the spa.  This is a quick fix if your home does not currently have one.\r\n\r\n4.)  Eazy Electric is one of the few Seattle electrical contractors that offer on site planning of your Spa install at no cost.  We say this because this project can become complicated and we want to ensure that your relaxing in your spa as soon as possible.\r\n\r\n5.)  Installing a hot tub is a dangerous job.  There is some residential work that any do-it-your self-er can handle, but I would encourage you to hire a qualified electrician for this project.\r\n\r\nI\'ll admit I knew becoming a electrician in Seattle was going to involve  crawling around in boiling hot attics with itchy insulation ending up  everywhere on me, like sand after a day at the beach.  Then there\'s the  awesome smell of dead rats and other lovely little critters I find in  the crawl spaces under houses that can put a damper on my day as an  electrical contractor.  But I will say that I don\'t mind it as much w